# Python — style and quality

## Minimal
- One clear responsibility per module/function; avoid premature abstractions and dead code.
- Prefer simple APIs and linear control flow over deep branching; extract only when duplication is real.

## Readable
- Descriptive names (verbs for functions, nouns for data); avoid opaque abbreviations.
- Explicit signatures: type hints on public boundaries (parameters/returns); `Optional`/`Union` when the type is not obvious.
- Formatting consistent with project tooling (e.g. ruff/black).

## Safe
- Never embed secrets or credentials in code; use environment variables or a secret store.
- Validate external input at the boundary (schema, range, format); fail explicitly with typed exceptions or structured errors.
- No bare `except:` or broad `except Exception:` without re-raise or targeted handling; no `eval`/`exec` on untrusted input.

## Refactorable
- Keep domain logic in pure functions or testable services; push side effects (I/O, DB) to the edges.
- Pass or encapsulate external dependencies (repositories, clients) instead of scattering imports in hot paths.
- Avoid mutable global state and implicit singletons that block tests and substitutions.

## Comments
- Prefer self-explanatory code over long comments.
- Comment only the **why** (domain constraints, temporary workarounds with ticket refs, non-obvious performance), not the **what** that the code already states.
